    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm running a linear regression on some housing price data and I'm seeing some weirdness with my residuals. They don't look normally distributed at all—lots of outliers and a heavy skew. What's the best way to handle this so my model stays valid?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You have a few options for dealing with non-normal residuals, but first, you should check if the problem is in your model assumptions or just the data itself. You can try transforming your dependent variable or the residuals themselves, like using a log transformation, or perhaps a Box-Cox transformation. If the data is heavily skewed, a log transformation is often a good first step to try and normalize the distribution. Remember, the goal is to make the residuals look more like a normal bell curve, not to just trick the model into fitting.",
      "source": "target",
