    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Thanks, the log transformation helped a bit but the skew is still pretty noticeable in certain price brackets. I've also got these massive outliers that are really pulling the regression line away from the bulk of the data. Is it better to just drop those points, or is there a more robust way to model this without losing too much information?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Dropping outliers is a risky move, especially when you're dealing with housing prices, as those outliers might be the most interesting, albeit noisy, data points. A better approach is to use more robust regression techniques, like **Robust Regression** methods. These methods, such as M-estimation or RANSAC, are less sensitive to extreme values than standard Ordinary Least Squares (OLS). You can also consider using **Winsorization**, which caps the extreme values at a certain percentile instead of outright deleting them.",
      "source": "target",
