    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. I'll look into RANSAC. Just curious though, when you talk about these \"extreme values\" fundamentally messing with the fit, is there a specific mathematical threshold where a point stops being just \"high variance\" and starts being a problem for the underlying assumptions of the model?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Mathematically, there isn't one single, universal threshold, but you can think of it in terms of leverage and influence. A point becomes a problem when it has a high **leverage**—meaning it's far out in the x-direction—and a large **residual**—meaning it's far off the regression line. A good heuristic, though not a strict rule, is to look at the standardized residuals. If a residual is several standard deviations away from zero (say, beyond 3 or 4 standard deviations), that point is definitely exerting a disproportionate influence.",
      "source": "target",
